{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f032557a-281a-4b63-9dc7-d98d1dd1dbde","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a standard .NET MAUI property — that's likely why it's having no effect. You need **platform-specific** configuration:\n\n**iOS** — disable safe area insets on the page:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n**Android** — draw behind system bars in `MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n}\n```\n\n**Also check for these common culprits:**\n\n1. **Page/layout padding** — ensure no `Padding` on the `ContentPage` or its root layout.\n2. **Shell/NavigationPage chrome** — if using `Shell`, set `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"` and `Shell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\"` on the page. For `NavigationPage`, use `NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"`.\n3. **Image sizing** — use `Aspect=\"AspectFill\"` on the `Image` so it actually fills the available space.\n\nMinimal working XAML:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"...\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n             Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n             Padding=\"0\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"75327f5c-8e4d-4202-ab85-af688161564f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` but still have padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. Let me check if there's relevant documentation or skill content in the repository that might help, but this seems like a general .NET MAUI knowledge question.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content:\n\n1. `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage is not a standard MAUI API - the user might be confused.\n\n\n2. On iOS, I need to use platform-specific markup like `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"false\"` to let content extend behind the status bar and home indicator.\n3. On Android, the approach is different - typically involving window-level settings to disable system window insets, though the exact API depends on the MAUI version.\n\nThe user might be referencing a custom `SafeAreaEdges` property that isn't part of standard MAUI, so I should clarify what the actual platform-specific approaches are for achieving edge-to-edge layouts. Setting up the Android side with `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false)` to let content draw behind system bars, and making sure there's no extra padding on the page or navigation chrome interfering with the edge-to-edge layout.","outputTokens":1328,"requestId":"1019:1EA4:4D74DEC:547FE9A:69FD36EE"},"id":"73528e2b-af59-44e1-9b43-616772870e08","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:06:17.600Z","parentId":"e3a4747f-eead-445a-a278-cca5e628afea"}
